Cueing effect in accuracies

Fit a glmer model to estimate the effects of cueing with a word and cueing with a visual frame on go/no-go accuracy. Calculate the cueing effects by comparing performance in each cueing condition to performance on the nocue trials.

I expect to find that cueing with a word leads to a bigger jump in go/no-go performance than cueing with a visual frame, because this demanding task requires the type of attentive state that words are better at activating than motivated cues like the visual frame.

Plot by-subject accuracies

  1. Compute by-subject accuracies
cueing_by_subj <- cueing %>% group_by(subj_id, cue_type) %>%
  summarize(accuracy = mean(is_correct))
  1. Arrange cue types on the x-axis
source("R/recoders.R")
cueing_by_subj$cue_type_int <- recode_cue_type_as_int(cueing_by_subj)
cueing_by_subj$cue_type_jit <- jitter_cue_type_int_by_subj(cueing_by_subj)
  1. Plot of subject accuracies by cue type
library(ggplot2)
library(scales)

by_subj_point_shape <- 1
by_subj_line_size <- 0.3

plot_bysubj <- ggplot(cueing_by_subj,
    aes(x = cue_type_int, y = accuracy)) +
  geom_point(aes(x = cue_type_jit, color = subj_id), shape = by_subj_point_shape) + 
  geom_line(aes(x = cue_type_jit, color = subj_id), size = by_subj_line_size) +
  scale_cue_type_int +
  scale_y_continuous("Accuracy", labels = percent) +
  theme(legend.position = "none")
plot_bysubj

Fit glmer model to raw accuracies

  1. Set the contrast codes
source("R/recoders.R")
cueing <- set_treatment_contrasts(cueing)
contrasts(cueing$cue_type)
##       frame sound
## nocue     0     0
## frame     1     0
## sound     0     1
  1. Predict likelihood of error from cue type
  • leaving the outlier subjects in for now
  • errors are false alarms and misses
library(lme4)
accuracy_mod <- glmer(data = cueing, family = "binomial",
  formula = is_correct ~ frame_v_nocue + sound_v_nocue + 
              (frame_v_nocue + sound_v_nocue || subj_id))
  ## the double pipe fits random intercepts and slopes without
  ## random effect correlations
summary(accuracy_mod)

Add model predictions to by-subject plot

  1. Get the model predictions
library(AICcmodavg)
x_preds <- data.frame(cue_type = c("nocue", "frame", "sound")) %>%
  set_treatment_contrasts()
x_preds$cue_type_int <- recode_cue_type_as_int(x_preds)

y_preds <- predictSE(accuracy_mod, x_preds, 
  type = "response", se = TRUE, print.matrix = TRUE)
predictions <- cbind(x_preds, y_preds) %>%
  rename(accuracy = fit, se = se.fit)
  1. By subject averages with model predictions overlayed
plot_accuracy_mod <- plot_bysubj +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = accuracy - se, ymax = accuracy + se),
    data = predictions, width = 0.05) +
  geom_line(aes(group = 1), data = predictions)

Conclusions

There are reliable boosts in target detection performance both when presented a visual frame and when presented a verbal cue. However, the cueing effect when presented a verbal cue is over twice the cueing effect from the visual frame.

library(broom)
coefficients <- tidy(accuracy_mod, effects = "fixed")
coefficients[2:3, c("term", "estimate", "std.error")]
##            term  estimate  std.error
## 2 frame_v_nocue 0.3995379 0.09541375
## 3 sound_v_nocue 0.8552262 0.10696007

Its also worth noting that the verbal cueing effect might be underestimated here as performance on verbal cue trials is near ceiling.

Comparing cueing effects

I cant simply compare the cueing effects by looking at the interaction between frame_v_nocue and sound_v_nocue because those variables are treatment contrast coded (the interaction term forces double dipping the data in the nocue condition).

As a temporary workaround, I can estimate the by-subject cueing effects by hand, and fit a simple lmer model on the summarized data.

  1. Summarize the frame and sound cueing effects for each subject. Starting with average accuracies in each cueing condition by subject, first cast the frame so that mean accuracy is split into three columns, one for each cueing condition. Calculate the cueing effects by taking the relevant differences in accuracy. Then melt the two difference columns back into tidy format.
library(reshape2)
cueing_effects <- cueing_by_subj %>%
  select(subj_id, cue_type, accuracy) %>%
  dcast(subj_id ~ cue_type, value.var = "accuracy") %>%
  mutate(
    frame_v_nocue = frame - nocue,
    sound_v_nocue = sound - nocue
  ) %>% select(subj_id, frame_v_nocue, sound_v_nocue) %>%
  melt(id.vars = "subj_id", variable.name = "cueing_effect", 
       value.name = "accuracy") %>%
  arrange(subj_id)
head(cueing_effects)
##    subj_id cueing_effect     accuracy
## 1 SPC3_301 frame_v_nocue  0.009782609
## 2 SPC3_301 sound_v_nocue  0.026782609
## 3 SPC3_302 frame_v_nocue  0.019963964
## 4 SPC3_302 sound_v_nocue -0.008516129
## 5 SPC3_303 frame_v_nocue  0.014551105
## 6 SPC3_303 sound_v_nocue  0.017003116
  1. Fit a simple lmer mod on the summarize data
comparison_mod <- lmer(data = cueing_effects,
  formula = accuracy ~ cueing_effect + (1|subj_id))
## It's ok to use lmer on accuracies here because
## we are comparing the means in two groups
summary(comparison_mod)
## Linear mixed model fit by REML ['lmerMod']
## Formula: accuracy ~ cueing_effect + (1 | subj_id)
##    Data: cueing_effects

Conclusions

As expected, the verbal cueing effect is reliably larger than the visual cueing effect.

t_val <- summary(comparison_mod)$coefficients[2, "t value"]
df_est <- length(cueing$subj_id %>% unique) - 1
p_est <- 1.0 - pt(t_val, df = df_est, lower.tail = TRUE)
p_est
## [1] 0.003631607

Cueing effect by trial type

Within each cueing condition, there are four types of trials: 1. Hit: Successful detection the target. 2. Miss: Failure to respond when the target was present. 3. False Alarm: Detection of a target that was not present. 4. Pass: No target and no response.

Count up the number of trials in each of the trial types above for each of the three cue types and plot the results.

source("R/recoders.R")
cueing$trial_type <- determine_trial_type(cueing)

trial_types_by_subj <- cueing %>% 
  group_by(subj_id, cue_type, trial_type) %>%
  summarize(count = n()) %>%
  group_by(subj_id, cue_type) %>%
  mutate(rate = count/sum(count)) %>%
  ungroup()
trial_types_by_subj

## 3  SPC3_301    nocue        miss     2 0.017391304

# position cue type on horizontal axis
trial_types_by_subj$cue_type_int <- recode_cue_type_as_int(trial_types_by_subj)
trial_types_by_subj$cue_type_jit <- jitter_cue_type_int_by_subj(trial_types_by_subj)

# label text will be used in facet headers
trial_types_by_subj$trial_type_lab <- label_trial_type(trial_types_by_subj)
# expected hit rates are 85% and 15%
reference_lines <- data.frame(
  trial_type_lab = c("hit", "pass"),
  expected = c(0.85, 0.15)
)
reference_lines$trial_type_lab <- label_trial_type(reference_lines)

ggplot(trial_types_by_subj, aes(y = rate)) +
  geom_point(aes(x = cue_type_jit, color = subj_id), shape = by_subj_point_shape) +
  geom_line(aes(x = cue_type_jit, color = subj_id), size = by_subj_line_size) +
  facet_wrap("trial_type_lab", ncol = 2, scales = "free_y") +
  geom_hline(aes(yintercept = expected), data = reference_lines, lty = 2) +
  scale_cue_type_int +
  scale_y_continuous("Percentage of Trials", labels = percent) +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

Conclusions

It seems that the verbal cue is improving accuracy by making people more likely to detect the target (not a decrease in false alarms, for example).

Cueing effect in RTs on hit trials

hit_trials <- filter(cueing, trial_type == 'hit')

Plot by-subject RTs

rts_by_subj <- hit_trials %>% group_by(subj_id, cue_type) %>%
  summarize(rt = mean(rt))

rts_by_subj$cue_type_int <- recode_cue_type_as_int(rts_by_subj)

plot_rts_by_subj <- ggplot(rts_by_subj,
    aes(x = cue_type_int, y = rt)) +

Fit lmer model to raw RTs

rt_mod <- lmer(rt ~ frame_v_nocue + sound_v_nocue +
                     (frame_v_nocue + sound_v_nocue || subj_id),
                   data = hit_trials)
summary(rt_mod)

Conclusions

Both types of cues facilitate faster responses when compared to no cue trials, but visual cues and verbal cues did not differ in cueing effects as measured in RTs.
